$\underset{20 \,g}{\mathrm{N}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}}+\underset{5 \mathrm{~g}}{3 H_{2(g)}} \rightleftharpoons 2 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}$<br/><br/> Ideally $28 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~N}_{2}$ reacts with $6 \mathrm{~g} \,\mathrm{H}_{2}$ limiting reagent is $\mathrm{N}_{2}$<br/><br/> $\therefore$ Amount of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ formed on reacting $20 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~N}_2$ is,
<br/><br/>
$$
\begin{aligned}
&=\frac{34 \times 20}{28}=24.28 \mathrm{~g} \\\\
&=1.42 \text { moles }
\end{aligned}
$$

We know,
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{gathered}
{[S]=\left[\mathrm{MT}^{-2}\right]} \\\\
{[\rho]=\left[\mathrm{ML}^{-3}\right]} \\\\
{[r]=\left[\mathrm{L}]\right.}
\end{gathered}
$$
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
\therefore \text { Dimension of } \mathrm{RHS} &=\frac{\left[\mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{-\frac{3}{2}}\right]\left[\mathrm{L}^{\frac{3}{2}}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{MT}^{-2}\right]^{\frac{3}{4}}} \\\\
&=\left[\mathrm{M}^{\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{3}{4}\right)} \mathrm{L}^{\left(-\frac{3}{2}+\frac{3}{2}\right)} \mathrm{T}^{\frac{6}{4}}\right]=\mathrm{M}^{-\frac{1}{4}} \mathrm{~L}^{0} \mathrm{~T}^{\frac{3}{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$
<br/><br/>dimension of L.H.S. = $[\mathrm{T}]$
<br/><br/>$\therefore$ Dimension of LHS $\neq$ Dimension of RHS.
